.TH "iucv_message_reply" 9 "iucv_message_reply" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
iucv_message_reply \- 
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" iucv_message_reply
.BI "(struct iucv_path *path "  ","
.BI "struct iucv_message *msg "  ","
.BI "u8 flags "  ","
.BI "void *reply "  ","
.BI "size_t size "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "path" 12
address of iucv path structure
.IP "msg" 12
address of iucv msg structure
.IP "flags" 12
how the reply is sent (IUCV_IPRMDATA, IUCV_IPPRTY, IUCV_IPBUFLST)
.IP "reply" 12
address of reply data buffer or address of struct iucv_array
.IP "size" 12
length of reply data buffer
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
This function responds to the two-way messages that you receive. You
must identify completely the message to which you wish to reply. ie,
pathid, msgid, and trgcls. Prmmsg signifies the data is moved into
the parameter list.

Returns the result from the CP IUCV call.
